As a cyclist myself, I agree with this sign.

I weigh about 70kg. My #ebike weighs about 22kg. Assuming I have some shopping or whatever in my panniers/backpack, that's roughly 100kg mass moving at up to 25km/h, or just under 7m/s

That's 700 kg·m/s which is a lot of momentum/energy. Certainly enough to do significant damage.

I will, of course, always slow down in areas where the path is shared, congested or narrow/twisting. Typically <10km/h or sometimes just accept I need to get off and walk.

(i) approve written guidelines that ensure library sections designated for minors under the age of 18 remain free of material containing obscenity, sexually explicit or other material deemed inappropriate for children or youth. All material containing such content must be weeded out of the library's collection or relocated to an adult section. Under this rule, any materials regarding transgender procedures, gender ideology, or the concept of more than two biological genders shall be considered inappropriate for children and youth. Age-appropriate materials regarding religion, history, biology, or human anatomy should not be construed to be against this rule.

(j) approve written selection criteria for minors that prevents the purchase or otherwise acquiring of any material advertised for consumers under the age of 18 which contain obscenity, sexually explicit or other material deemed inappropriate for children or youth. Age-appropriate materials regarding religion, history, biology, or human anatomy should not be construed to be against this rule.

(k) approve written guidelines establishing that library cards issued to minors under the age of 18 shall prohibit the checkout of materials from the library's adult collections. The standard library card issued to all minors under the age of 18 must be a restricted card. A library may also issue a non-restricted minor card granting access to adult collections, provided that written consent is obtained from the minor's parent or legal guardian.

(l) recognize and comply with all state code, rules, and definitions adopted by the ALS executive board.
